'''Lewis Ferguson''' (born 24 August 1999) is a Scottish professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as an [[attacking midfielder]] for [[Serie A]] club [[Bologna FC 1909|Bologna]], whom he [[Captain (association football)|captain]]s, and the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]].

After playing youth football for [[Rangers F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Rangers]] and [[Hamilton Academical F.C. Reserves and Academy|Hamilton Academical]], Ferguson made his senior debut for [[Hamilton Academical F.C.|the latter club]] in the 2017–18 season. After four seasons with [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] he moved to Italian club Bologna in 2022.

A Scotland youth international, Ferguson made his senior debut in 2021.

==Early life==
Lewis Ferguson was born on 24 August 1999 in [[Hamilton, South Lanarkshire]].<ref name="Soccerway">{{cite web |url=https://uk.soccerway.com/players/lewis-ferguson/451116/ |title=L. Ferguson: Summary |website=Soccerway |publisher=Perform Group |access-date=23 November 2024}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Hamilton Academical===
Ferguson is a graduate of the [[Hamilton Academical F.C.|Hamilton Academical]] youth system<ref>{{Cite web |date=17 May 2018 |title=Departures |work=Hamilton Academical Website |url=https://www.hamiltonacciesfc.co.uk/departures/ |access-date=27 July 2018 |publisher=Hamilton Academical F.C. |archive-date=27 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180727181026/https://www.hamiltonacciesfc.co.uk/departures/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> after earlier being part of the setup at [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/lewis-ferguson-reveals-rangers-pain-34083168|title=Lewis Ferguson opens up on heartbreaking Rangers exit and his gnawing pain|first=Alan|last=Galindo|date=11 November 2024|website=Daily Record}}</ref><ref name="rfc2009">{{Cite web |year=2009 |title=Youth Player Under 11s Team Group – Murray Park |url=https://www.rangerspics.com/previous-seasons/rangers-team-previous-seasons-2009-10-squad-11s-u12s-team-headshot/soccer-rangers-youth-player-11s-team-1932623.html |access-date=27 July 2018 |website=Rangers Pics |archive-date=6 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201106010210/https://www.rangerspics.com/previous-seasons/rangers-team-previous-seasons-2009-10-squad-11s-u12s-team-headshot/soccer-rangers-youth-player-11s-team-group-1932623.html |url-status=dead }}</ref> He made his senior debut for Hamilton on 20 January 2018,<ref name="2017-18" /> and became a regular in the team in the latter part of the 2017–18 season, replacing [[Greg Docherty]] who had moved to Rangers.<ref name="Aberdeen" />

With his contract due to expire at the end of that season, Ferguson signed a pre-contract agreement with [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] in May 2018.<ref name="Aberdeen">{{Cite web |date=5 May 2018 |title=Aberdeen: Lewis Ferguson agrees pre-contract move from Hamilton |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44016756 |access-date=5 May 2018 |website=[[BBC Sport]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |first=Daryn |last=Macrae |date=4 June 2018 |title=Hamilton want £900k from Aberdeen for Lewis Ferguson |url=https://stv.tv/sport/football/1417089-hamilton-want-900k-from-aberdeen-for-lewis-ferguson/ |access-date=27 July 2018 |publisher=STV |archive-date=27 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180727181020/https://stv.tv/sport/football/1417089-hamilton-want-900k-from-aberdeen-for-lewis-ferguson/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> He was one of seven first-team players who left Hamilton at the end of the 2017–18 season.<ref>{{Cite web |first=Craig |last=Fowler |date=14 May 2018 |title=Hamilton Accies announce departure of seven first-team players |url=https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/teams/hamilton-accies/hamilton-accies-announce-departure-of-seven-first-team-players-1-4739307 |access-date=15 May 2018 |website=[[The Scotsman]]}}</ref>

===Aberdeen===
Ferguson made his competitive debut for Aberdeen on 26 July 2018, in the first leg of a [[2018–19 UEFA Europa League qualifying phase and play-off round (Main Path)#Second qualifying round|Europa League]] tie against [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] at [[Pittodrie Stadium]].<ref name="2018-19" /><ref>{{Cite web |first=Tom |last=English |date=26 July 2018 |title=Aberdeen 1–1 Burnley |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44938522 |access-date=27 July 2018 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> He scored his first senior goal in the second leg at [[Turf Moor]] – a "stunning overhead kick" – although Burnley eventually won the tie on aggregate after [[Overtime (sports)#Association football|extra time]].<ref>{{Cite web |first=Chris |last=McLaughlin |date=2 August 2018 |title=Burnley 3–1 Aberdeen: Premier League side progress 4–2 on aggregate |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45005829 |access-date=2 August 2018 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 28 October, he helped Aberdeen to reach the [[2018 Scottish League Cup Final]] by scoring the only goal of the semi-final against Rangers at [[Hampden Park]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=28 October 2018 |title=No Scottish League Cup final for Gerrard as Ferguson sends Aberdeen through |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/oct/28/scottish-leagu-cup-aberdeen-rangers-steven-gerrard-match-report |access-date=28 October 2018 |website=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> By the end of the calendar year, he had also scored three league goals, all in the closing minutes of each fixture, with two of them (a free kick against [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]]<ref>{{Cite web |date=4 November 2018 |title=Kilmarnock 1–2 Aberdeen: Lewis Ferguson the hero again as Dons come from behind |url=https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/teams/aberdeen/kilmarnock-1-2-aberdeen-lewis-ferguson-the-hero-again-as-dons-come-from-behind-1-4824323 |access-date=4 January 2019 |website=[[The Scotsman]]}}</ref> and another overhead kick against [[Livingston F.C.|Livingston]])<ref>{{Cite web |first=Scott |last=Davie |date=11 December 2018 |title=Aberdeen 3–2 Livingston: Lewis Ferguson nets overhead-kick winner |url=https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/competitions/premiership/aberdeen-3-2-livingston-lewis-ferguson-nets-overhead-kick-winner-1-4842854/amp |access-date=4 January 2019 |website=The Scotsman}}</ref> winning the matches for his team.

In February 2019, Ferguson extended his contract with Aberdeen, keeping him at the club until 2024.<ref>{{Cite web |date=21 February 2019 |title=Aberdeen: Lewis Ferguson signs two-year contract extension until 2024 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47320191 |access-date=21 February 2019 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> In April, he played at Hampden Park again, but this time was sent off for a dangerous challenge as Aberdeen lost to [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] in the semi-final of the [[2018–19 Scottish Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=14 April 2019 |title=Scottish Cup Semi-final (2): Aberdeen 0 Celtic 3 |url=https://www.hampdenpark.co.uk/events/scottish-cup-semi-final-(2).html |access-date=6 May 2019 |publisher=Hampden Park}}</ref> In May 2019, he was nominated for the season's [[PFA Scotland Young Player of the Year]]; the award was won by [[Ryan Kent]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=5 May 2019 |title=Player of the Year: Old Firm quartet vie for PFA Scotland top prize |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/scotland/48124177 |access-date=6 May 2019 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

Ferguson was the club's top scorer during the 2020–21 season, with 10 goals in 41 appearances.<ref name = request>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/57178643 |title=Aberdeen: Lewis Ferguson hands in transfer request after bid |website=BBC Sport |date=19 May 2021 |accessdate=19 May 2021}}</ref> Aberdeen rejected an offer from [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] for Ferguson in May 2021, after which he submitted a written transfer request.<ref name = request/>

===Bologna===
On 12 July 2022, Italian club [[Bologna FC 1909|Bologna]] announced the signing of Ferguson for an undisclosed transfer fee.<ref>{{Cite web |date=12 July 2022 |title=Lewis Ferguson joins Bologna |url=https://www.bolognafc.it/en/lewis-ferguson-joins-bologna/ |access-date=12 July 2022 |website=BolognaFC.it}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/62140194|title=Ferguson completes move to Bologna from Aberdeen|date=12 July 2022|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> He made his debut as a substitute in a 2–0 away defeat to [[A.C. Milan|Milan]] on 27 August 2022,<ref name="dailyrecord">{{cite news |title=Lewis Ferguson on scary Bologna stardom as Scotland star opens up on Serie A 'wow' factor |url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/lewis-ferguson-scary-bologna-stardom-28613087 |work=Daily Record |date=30 November 2022 |accessdate=2 January 2023 }}</ref> and made two more substitute appearances before his first start against [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]] on 16 October.<ref>{{cite news |first=Mark |last=McDougall |title=Lewis Ferguson given first Serie A start as ex Aberdeen man handed Bologna chance vs Napoli |url=https://www.footballscotland.co.uk/spfl/lewis-ferguson-given-first-serie-25277274 |website=footballscotland |date=16 October 2022 |accessdate=3 January 2023 }}</ref> His first goal came a week later, the second in a 2–0 win at home to [[U.S. Lecce|Lecce]], and he scored again the following week – the equaliser in a 2–1 away win over [[A.C. Monza|Monza]].<ref name="dailyrecord"/> On 12 November 2022, he scored Bologna's third goal in a 3–0 win over [[U.S. Sassuolo Calcio|Sassuolo]], a curling effort from the edge of the penalty area after a [[Push and run|one-two]] with [[Nicolás Domínguez]] that was later named the [[Serie A]] goal of the month for November 2022.<ref>{{cite news |first=Joel |last=Sked |title=Lewis Ferguson: Serie A stand-out, Thiago Motta favourite, Bologna chant, perfect Scotland opportunity |url=https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/international/lewis-ferguson-serie-a-stand-out-thiago-motta-favourite-bologna-chant-perfect-scotland-opportunity-3918132 |work=The Scotsman |date=14 November 2022 |accessdate=3 January 2023 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Goal of the Month |url=https://www.legaseriea.it/it/award/crypto-com-goal-of-the-month |publisher=Lega Serie A |accessdate=2 January 2023 }}</ref> Ferguson started 28 games for Bologna during the 2022–23 season as they finished ninth in [[2022–23 Serie A|Serie A]].<ref name = bfccontract/> He scored seven goals during the season, which was the highest tally by a Scottish player in an Italian league season since [[Denis Law]] played for Torino in [[1961–62 Serie A|1961–62]].<ref name = bfccontract/>

In July 2023, Ferguson signed a new contract with Bologna that is due to run until the end of the 2026–27 season.<ref name = bfccontract>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/66210905 |title=Lewis Ferguson: Bologna extend Scotland midfielder's contract until 2027 |website=BBC Sport |date=15 July 2023 |accessdate=15 July 2023}}</ref> In October 2023 he became Bologna's captain,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.footballscotland.co.uk/scots-abroad/lewis-fergusons-bologna-reputation-grows-27821382|title=Lewis Ferguson's Bologna reputation grows as ex Aberdeen star named captain|first=Mark|last=McDougall|date=1 October 2023|website=Football Scotland}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aberdeenlive.news/sport/football/football-news/lewis-ferguson-captains-bologna-former-8795218|title=Lewis Ferguson given captain's armband for Bologna in 3-0 win|first=Ciaran|last=Shanks|date=1 October 2023|website=Aberdeen Live}}</ref> and he continued in that role,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aberdeenlive.news/sport/football/football-news/former-aberdeen-star-lewis-ferguson-8966833|title=Former Aberdeen star Lewis Ferguson captains Bologna again in first away victory|first=Anthony|last=Evans|date=11 December 2023|website=Aberdeen Live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/lewis-ferguson-shows-bologna-hes-32265904|title=Ferguson labelled Bologna 'warrior' as boss says 'he's always a ten out of ten'|first=Mark|last=Walker|date=4 March 2024|website=Daily Record}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/articles/cgxdy3qzn3ko|title=Souness lauds Ferguson's Italian job|date=4 March 2024|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> until suffering a knee injury in April 2024.<ref name = 2024knee/><ref name = surgery>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/articles/cv2x1jgz2q0o |title=Ferguson's operation goes well |website=BBC Sport |date=18 April 2024 |accessdate=19 April 2024}}</ref> He later said it would be six or seven months before he could re-start training.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/articles/c9wz2e7nw2mo|title=Lewis Ferguson: Scotland and Bologna star on 'long journey back' from injury|date=8 May 2024|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

Ferguson became the top Scottish goalscorer in Serie A history on 23 December 2023, overtaking Denis Law, when he scored the only goal in a 1–0 win against [[Atalanta BC|Atalanta]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/67813683 |title=Lewis Ferguson: Bologna midfielder overtakes Denis Law's Serie A record |website=BBC Sport |date=23 December 2023 |accessdate=24 December 2023}}</ref> He was named the Serie A midfielder of the year for the 2023–24 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/articles/cd13p97znw4o|title=Scotland: Bologna's Ferguson named best Serie A midfielder|date=6 May 2024|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

On 29 October 2024, Ferguson was named in a matchday squad for the first time in over six months, remaining on the bench as Bologna beat [[Cagliari Calcio|Cagliari]] 2–0.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/red-hot-scotland-duo-help-napoli-show-title-credentials-at-san-siro-but-lewis-ferguson-forced-to-wait-4845226|title=Red-hot Scotland duo help Napoli show title credentials at San Siro - but Lewis Ferguson forced to wait|last=Atkinson|first=Mark|date=29 October 2024|work=The Scotsman|access-date=30 October 2024}}</ref> He said that "the Scottish mentality" helped him recover from his injury quicker than expected.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/articles/cr5m629g09do|title=Lewis Ferguson credits 'Scottish mentality' for Bologna return|date=28 October 2024|website=BBC Sport|access-date=30 October 2024}}</ref> He made his return to the pitch in Bologna's 1–0 win over Lecce on 2 November, coming on as an 82-minute substitute for [[Remo Freuler]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://football-italia.net/ferguson-hopes-after-six-month-lay-off/|title=Bologna coach has high hopes for Scotland international Ferguson after return from six-month injury lay-off|last=Young|first=Peter|date=2 November 2024|work=Football Italia}}</ref> Later that month, he extended his Bologna contract until 2028<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/c154y8307p9o|title=Lewis Ferguson: Scotland midfielder signs new Bologna deal|date=22 November 2024|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> and made his [[UEFA Champions League]] debut against [[LOSC Lille|Lille]], in which he played a full 90 minutes for the first time in over seven months.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/scottish-premiership/latest-premiership-news/lewis-fergusons-big-bologna-milestone-ends-in-despair-as-scotland-stars-involved-in-champions-league-drama-4886608|title=Ferguson's big Bologna milestone ends in Champions League despair|last=Atkinson|first=Mark|date=27 November 2024|website=The Scotsman}}</ref>

Ferguson captained Bologna to their first final in 51 years, beating Empoli 2–1 (5–1 on aggregate), on 30 April 2025 to reach the [[2025 Coppa Italia final|Coppa Italia final]].<ref name=cophist>{{cite news|url=https://www.thenational.scot/sport/25114320.lewis-ferguson-chance-emulate-rangers-icon-coppa-italia-final/|title=Lewis Ferguson chance to emulate Rangers icon in Coppa Italia final|last=Lindsay|first=Matthew|date=25 April 2025|work=The Scotsman}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aberdeenlive.news/sport/football/lewis-ferguson-dreaming-bologna-history-10141724|title=Lewis Ferguson dreaming of Bologna history as ex-Dons ace leads side to first final in 51 years|first1=Scott|last1=Burns|first2=Ruaraidh|last2=Britton|date=29 April 2025|website=Aberdeen Live}}</ref> Ferguson was captain again winning the final 1–0 versus Milan on 14 May 2025.<ref name=copfin>{{Cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2025/05/14/italy/coppa-italia/ac-milan/bologna-fc-1909/4405387/|title=AC Milan vs. Bologna - 14 May 2025 - Soccerway|website=int.soccerway.com}}</ref> Ferguson emulated [[Graeme Souness]] to become the second Scotsman to win the Coppa Italia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2025/may/15/bologna-unlikely-coppa-italia-triumph-ends-long-wait-for-silverware|title=Bologna's unlikely Coppa Italia triumph ends long wait for silverware|first=Nicky|last=Bandini|work=The Guardian |date=15 May 2025}}</ref>

==International career==
Ferguson was called up by the [[Scotland national under-19 football team|Scotland under-19]] team in August 2017,<ref>{{Cite web |date=26 August 2017 |title=International call up for Lewis Ferguson |url=https://www.hamiltonacciesfc.co.uk/international-call-up-for-lewis-ferguson/ |access-date=20 January 2018 |publisher=Hamilton Academical F.C. |archive-date=27 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180727181029/https://www.hamiltonacciesfc.co.uk/international-call-up-for-lewis-ferguson/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> and he went on to make appearances at the under-19, [[Scotland national under-20 football team|under-20]] and [[Scotland national under-21 football team|Scotland under-21]] levels.<ref name = SFA>{{SFA Profile|id=182030|name=Lewis Ferguson}}</ref> Ferguson received his first call-up to the senior [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] squad in August 2021 for games against [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]], [[Moldova national football team|Moldova]] and [[Austria national football team|Austria]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/58317930 |title=Scotland: Zander Clark, Liam Kelly & Lewis Ferguson called up for World Cup qualifiers |date=24 August 2021 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=24 August 2021 |publisher=BBC}}</ref> He made his debut against Denmark on 1 September 2021 in a 2–0 away loss, coming on for [[Billy Gilmour]] in added time.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[FIFA]]|url=https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/mens/worldcup/qatar2022/qualifiers/uefa/match-center/400155658|title=Denmark v Scotland game report|date=1 September 2021}}</ref>

He suffered a knee injury in April 2024 which required surgery and put his participation at [[UEFA Euro 2024|Euro 2024]] into doubt.<ref name = 2024knee>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/68819138 |title=Lewis Ferguson: Knee surgery puts Scotland midfielder's Euro hopes in serious doubt |website=BBC Sport |date=15 April 2024 |accessdate=16 April 2024}}</ref><ref name = surgery/> After missing the tournament due to injury, he said his "time would come" with the national team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cpee909znglo|title=Lewis Ferguson confident 'time will come' with Scotland after injury setback|date=9 June 2024|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> He was recalled by the national team in March 2025.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cr52zdm88pro|title=Uncapped teenagers Lennon Miller & James Wilson named in Scotland squad for Greece tie|date=11 March 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

In October 2025 Ferguson scored his first goal in a full international, the second goal in a 3&ndash;1 win against [[Greece national football team|Greece]] during [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification]].<ref name = greece>{{cite web |url=https://news.stv.tv/sport/scotland-3-1-greece-lewis-ferguson-lives-his-dream-with-first-scotland-goal |title=Scotland 3-1 Greece: Lewis Ferguson lives his dream with first Scotland goal |website=STV News |date=9 October 2025 |accessdate=17 October 2025}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Lewis is the son of [[Derek Ferguson]] and nephew of [[Barry Ferguson]], both former professional footballers with clubs including Rangers, and the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]].<ref>{{Cite web |first=Andy |last=McGilvray |date=16 December 2017 |title=Derek Ferguson says it will be a proud moment if and when son Lewis makes first-team debut for Hamilton |url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/derek-ferguson-says-proud-moment-11695584 |access-date=20 January 2018 |website=Daily Record}}</ref> His cousin [[Kyle Ferguson]] is also a footballer (they were teammates as children in the Rangers academy).<ref name="rfc2009"/>

He and his partner welcomed their first child, a daughter, in November 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/lewis-ferguson-scary-bologna-stardom-28613087|title=Lewis Ferguson opens up on his life changing move to Italy|first=Scott|last=Burns|date=30 November 2022|website=Daily Record}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aberdeenlive.news/sport/football/football-news/former-aberdeen-star-lewis-ferguson-8590972|title=Lewis Ferguson on meeting Jose Mourinho and his best opponents so far in Italy|first1=Scott|last1=Burns|first2=Anthony|last2=Evans|date=12 July 2023|website=Aberdeen Live}}</ref> Another daughter was born in 2025.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/25149656.lewis-ferguson-linked-napoli-wee-italian-girl/|title=Lewis Ferguson on being linked with Napoli and his 'wee Italian girl'|last=Lindsay|first=Matthew|date=13 May 2025|work=The Herald|accessdate=13 May 2025|url-access=subscription}}</ref>

